          "text": "Now I have the full picture. Let me write the plan.\n\n---\n\n## Plan: Line History Changes for `modified_lines` Support\n\n### Problem 0: Data Model Gap in the Existing Plan (Needs Amendment)\n\nThis is the most important thing to flag before touching `line_history.rs`.\n\n`modified_line_ranges` is stored as `Option<Vec<(u32, u32)>>` — new-file coordinates only. For `reconstruct_diff_ops` to correctly advance `old_pos` through a Replace hunk, it needs to know **both** sides: how many new-file lines the hunk produced AND how many old-file lines it consumed. Without the old extent, every line mapping after the first modified range would be wrong (old_pos would be left at the wrong position).\n\n**Required amendment to already-completed todos:**\n\nChange `WorkingLogEntry.modified_line_ranges` from `Option<Vec<(u32, u32)>>` to `Option<Vec<((u32, u32), (u32, u32))>>`, where each tuple is `(old_range, new_range)`. This is consistent with how `capture_diff_slices` returns a `DiffOp::Replace { old_index, old_len, new_index, new_len }` — both sides are naturally available at compute time.\n\nIn `FileChangeDetail.modified_lines`, serialize each pair as `\"old_start-old_end:new_start-new_end\"` (e.g. `\"3-5:3-7\"`). This reuses the existing compact range syntax but adds a `:` separator to encode both halves. A custom formatter is needed alongside the existing `format_line_range_tuple`.\n\nThe downstream todos (`compute-ranges`, `post-commit-wire`) are still pending so they haven't hardcoded the `(u32, u32)` type yet — this amendment lands before those are written.\n\n---\n\n### Changes to `line_history.rs`\n\nThere are six distinct changes, in dependency order.\n\n---\n\n#### 1. Extend `DiffOp` with a `Replace` variant\n\nThe local `DiffOp` enum needs a variant to carry both sides of a Replace hunk so `map_new_to_old` and `reverse_through_insert` can advance both `old_pos` and `new_pos` correctly.\n\n```rust\nenum DiffOp {\n    Equal(usize),\n    Delete(usize),\n    Insert(usize),\n    Replace(usize, usize),  // (old_len, new_len)\n}\n```\n\n---\n\n#### 2. Add `parse_modified_ranges`\n\nA new parser for the `\"old_start-old_end:new_start-new_end\"` format. Extract the single-range parsing into a helper to avoid duplicating the `split_once('-')` logic.\n\n```rust\nfn parse_single_range(s: &str) -> Option<(u32, u32)> {\n    if let Some((start, end)) = s.split_once('-') {\n        Some((start.parse().ok()?, end.parse().ok()?))\n    } else {\n        let n = s.parse().ok()?;\n        Some((n, n))\n    }\n}\n\nfn parse_modified_ranges(ranges: &[String]) -> Vec<((u32, u32), (u32, u32))> {\n    ranges\n        .iter()\n        .filter_map(|s| {\n            let (old_part, new_part) = s.split_once(':')?;\n            Some((parse_single_range(old_part)?, parse_single_range(new_part)?))\n        })\n        .collect()\n}\n```\n\nThe existing `parse_line_ranges` can be refactored to call `parse_single_range` instead of duplicating the logic.\n\n---\n\n#### 3. Update `reconstruct_diff_ops`\n\nNew signature:\n\n```rust\nfn reconstruct_diff_ops(\n    added: &[(u32, u32)],\n    deleted: &[(u32, u32)],\n    modified: &[((u32, u32), (u32, u32))],  // (old_range, new_range)\n) -> Vec<DiffOp>\n```\n\nThe core insight: `Delete` and `Replace` are both triggered by their **old-file** start position. `Insert` is triggered by its **new-file** start position. On each iteration, compute the \"next old-side event\" as `min(next_del_old_start, next_mod_old_start)`, then proceed with the existing two-cursor logic extended for the Replace case.\n\nKey rules for the Replace arm:\n- Emit `DiffOp::Replace(old_len, new_len)` \n- Advance **both** `old_pos += old_len` and `new_pos += new_len` (unlike Delete which only advances `old_pos`, and Insert which only advances `new_pos`)\n- After emitting a Replace, check if `new_pos` now coincides with the next pure Insert start — if so, emit it on the same iteration\n\nPseudocode for the combined branch:\n\n```rust\n// Determine next old-side event\nlet next_old_event: Option<(EventKind, u32)> = {\n    let d = deleted.get(del_idx).map(|(s, _)| (EventKind::Del, *s));\n    let m = modified.get(mod_idx).map(|((s, _), _)| (EventKind::Mod, *s));\n    match (d, m) {\n        (None, x) | (x, None) => x,\n        (Some(a), Some(b)) => Some(if a.1 <= b.1 { a } else { b }),\n    }\n};\n\nlet gap_to_old = next_old_event.map(|(_, s)| s - old_pos).unwrap_or(u32::MAX);\nlet gap_to_add = added.get(add_idx).map(|(s, _)| s - new_pos).unwrap_or(u32::MAX);\nlet eq = gap_to_old.min(gap_to_add);\n\nif eq > 0 { ops.push(DiffOp::Equal(eq as usize)); old_pos += eq; new_pos += eq; }\n\nif let Some((kind, _)) = next_old_event.filter(|(_, s)| *s == old_pos) {\n    match kind {\n        EventKind::Del => { /* existing Delete logic */ }\n        EventKind::Mod => {\n            let ((_, old_end), (_, new_end)) = modified[mod_idx];\n            let old_len = (old_end - old_pos + 1) as usize;\n            let new_len = (new_end - new_pos + 1) as usize; // new_pos == new_start here\n            ops.push(DiffOp::Replace(old_len, new_len));\n            old_pos += old_len as u32;\n            new_pos += new_len as u32;\n            mod_idx += 1;\n        }\n    }\n}\n// Then: check if new_pos == next add_start and emit Insert (existing logic)\n```\n\n---\n\n#### 4. Update `map_new_to_old`\n\nAdd a `modified` parameter and handle `DiffOp::Replace`. The semantics: a modified line has no 1:1 old-file counterpart → `None`. Crucially, both `old_pos` and `new_pos` advance by their respective lengths.\n\n```rust\nDiffOp::Replace(old_n, new_n) => {\n    let old_n = *old_n as u32;\n    let new_n = *new_n as u32;\n    if new_line >= new_pos && new_line < new_pos + new_n {\n        return None; // line was replaced\n    }\n    old_pos += old_n;\n    new_pos += new_n;\n}\n```\n\nUpdated signature:\n```rust\nfn map_new_to_old(\n    new_line: u32,\n    added: &[(u32, u32)],\n    deleted: &[(u32, u32)],\n    modified: &[((u32, u32), (u32, u32))],\n) -> Option<u32>\n```\n\n---\n\n#### 5. Update `reverse_through_insert`\n\nSame signature change. Handle `DiffOp::Replace` by capturing `pre_delete_old_pos` before advancing `old_pos`, then returning it if `new_line` falls inside the new range. This mirrors exactly what happens for the Delete→Insert sequence today.\n\n```rust\nDiffOp::Replace(old_n, new_n) => {\n    let old_n = *old_n as u32;\n    let new_n = *new_n as u32;\n    pre_delete_old_pos = old_pos;       // start of replaced old range\n    old_pos += old_n;\n    if new_line >= new_pos && new_line < new_pos + new_n {\n        return pre_delete_old_pos;\n    }\n    new_pos += new_n;\n    pre_delete_old_pos = old_pos;\n}\n```\n\n---\n\n#### 6. Update `find_checkpoints_that_touched_line`\n\nParse `detail.modified_lines` and thread it through the updated function calls:\n\n```rust\nlet added    = parse_line_ranges(&detail.added_lines);\nlet deleted  = parse_line_ranges(&detail.deleted_lines);\nlet modified = parse_modified_ranges(&detail.modified_lines);  // new\n\nmatch map_new_to_old(current_line, &added, &deleted, &modified) {\n    None => {\n        matched.push(/* ... */);\n        current_line = reverse_through_insert(current_line, &added, &deleted, &modified);\n    }\n    Some(old_line) => {\n        current_line = old_line;\n    }\n}\n```\n\n---\n\n### Changes Required to Other Todos\n\n| Todo | Impact |\n|---|---|\n| `working-log-field` (completed) | Change type from `Option<Vec<(u32,u32)>>` to `Option<Vec<((u32,u32),(u32,u32))>>` |\n| `file-change-detail` (completed) | No field change needed; document that `modified_lines` strings use `\"old:new\"` paired format |\n| `compute-ranges` (in_progress) | Return 4-tuple `(added, deleted, modified_old_ranges, modified_new_ranges)` and pair them when storing; or store as `Vec<((u32,u32),(u32,u32))>` directly |\n| `post-commit-wire` (pending) | Use a new `format_modified_range` formatter when building `modified_lines` strings |\n